# Demo and Documentation Patterns

## Demo Page Structure

Located in `packages/example/src/pages/`, each component should have comprehensive demos:

```tsx
// Demo page structure
export function ComponentDemo() {
  return (
    <div className="demo-container">
      <div className="demo-header">
        <h1>Component Name</h1>
        <p>Brief description of functionality</p>
      </div>

      <div className="demo-section">
        <h2>Basic Usage</h2>
        <div className="demo-item">
          <label>Example label:</label>
          <Component {...basicProps} />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  )
}
```

## Demo Categories

1. **Basic Usage**: Simple, common use cases
2. **Advanced Features**: Complex configurations and edge cases
3. **Customization**: Custom rendering and styling examples
4. **Interactive Examples**: User can modify props and see changes
5. **Performance Demos**: Large datasets and stress testing

## CSS for Demo Pages

- Consistent spacing with demo sections
- Responsive design for mobile/desktop
- Clear visual hierarchy
- Accessible color schemes
- Interactive elements should have hover states

## Router Configuration

Add new demo routes in `packages/example/src/router.tsx`:

```tsx
{
  path: '/component/feature',
  component: ComponentFeatureDemo,
  label: 'Feature Description',
}
```

## Documentation Guidelines

- Include real-world use cases
- Show both code and visual examples
- Explain when to use different props/configurations
- Demonstrate accessibility features
- Include performance considerations
- Add troubleshooting common issues

## Data for Demos

- Use realistic, representative data
- Include edge cases (empty data, large datasets)
- Provide multiple data formats when applicable
- Mock data should be reusable across demos
